            <p>1816 De Lancey Place.<lb/>
                Wednesday Dec<hi rend="sup">r</hi> 23<hi rend="sup">rd</hi> 1891.<lb/></p>
            <p>My dear Mr Morais&#45;&#45;<lb/></p>
            <p>I have been much<lb/> distressed&#44; to hear of your<lb/> illness&#44; and have <hi rend="underline">regretted</hi><lb/> that I could not go&#44; to<lb/> enquire after you&#44; and<lb/> express my regret at your<lb/> sufferings.  I know that<lb/> you are tendered by<lb/> loving hands&#44; &#38; hearts&#44;<lb/> and that your daughter<lb/> Nina&#33; has come from<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>afar&#59; to nurse and<lb/> comfort you&#44; &#38; I<lb/> have nothing to offer<lb/> you&#44; but my &#34;Prayers&#34;<lb/> which I know&#44; I am<lb/> joined&#44; by your whole<lb/> congregation&#33;<lb/></p>
            <p><sic>ever</sic> respectfully&#44; and<lb/> affectionately&#44; your Friend&#44;<lb/> Mrs Alfred Mordecai<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
